@Node quick "Quick Guide"
@{B}Interface Guide@{UB}

Here is a quick guide to get you started:

Enter your search criteria, which must be one word and no wildcards (But see
@{" To-Do " Link todo}), in to the top-left box.

Press return to execute the search.

Criteria matches should appear in the listview below the box. Select one and
the subject's text should appear in the listview at the bottom.

At the same time, some of the gadgets on the right should activate, allowing
you to view any of them upon clicking. At any time you may save the
text by selecting the "Edit/Save Text" menu.

Thats all there is to it! You may select any of the other search matches from
the results list, or enter a new search criteria. Any Subject entries with a
WI: prefix means a match has been found in the World Info directory on the
CD. These subjects are treated in the same way as the main subjects.

If no matches appear, enable "Use WorldInfo" and/or "Use People-Mess" from
the Settings menu if you haven't done so already, and search again. Use these
especially if you are searching for a particular person or country.

Note: Searching the "People-Mess" archive may take some time.

@EndNode

@Node viewers "Settings"
@{B}Viewers@{UB}

Clicking on the textgadgets on the right of the window brings up a file
requester for you to select an appropriate viewer for the type of file.

The selected viewer will appear in the string gadget to the left, allowing
you to put in any arguments the viewer can accept. Please leave a space
between the viewer name and it's arguments.
         
The default viewers are all on the encyclopedia disk, but have single letters
for names for some reason. These are copied to your hard disk upon
installation of the encyclopedia, and are renamed to their proper names.

Here is a list of the viewers used along with their "proper names".

B- DSound        Sound player by Dave Schreiber.
E- Noiseplayer   Music module player. Use -m1 for argument by Jolyon Ralph.
F- Play16        Sound sample player by Thomas Wenzel.
L- Visage        Picture viewer by Magnus Holmgren.
M- VT            Picture viewer and animation player by Thomas Krehbiel.

For viewing text: more, multiview or a word processor may be used as well as
EpicES's listview.

Stefan Boberg's LhA is also located in this directory and is used by EpicES
to extract files from the People-MESS.lha archive.

@EndNode

@Node indexfiles "Settings"
@{B}Index Files@{UB}

Select the index files by clicking on the buttons to the right of the
string gadgets.

The default location for the index files is in the "Menufiles/Indexfiles/"
directory.

The World Info files are in the "Menufiles/WORLDinfo/" directory.

Last, but not least, the People-MESS archive can normally be found in
"Menufiles/Vin-archive/".

@EndNode

@Node font "Settings"
@{B}Font@{UB}

Select the 8x8 font to be used throughout the interface and menus.

@EndNode


@Node trouble "Troubleshooting"
@{B}Troubleshooting@{UB}

In this section I have listed some problems along with possible solutions.
But if you are still having problems, please don't hesitate to report them
to @{" me " Link me}, and I will do my best to fix them.

* If you are unable to view any of the multi-media files associated with
  a subject, even if the gadgets are active, then check the viewers settings
  ("Settings/@{" Viewers " Link viewers}" menu). The default ones should be on the CD.

@EndNode

